Part 1: Use and Maintenance Manual
1. General System Architecture
This application is an entirely client-side, local, serverless polyphonic synthesizer and harmony sequencer. It runs natively under the file:/// protocol without compiling steps, package managers, or installation setups.
The application utilizes a strict unidirectional data flow inside global application state wrappers (window.App), mirroring Scheme/Functional programming styles where operations are cleanly decoupled:
Data Models are immutable objects passed down as configuration inputs.
UI Elements are factories that return pure, isolated DOM tree nodes without managing long-term internal memory.
[index.html Orchestrator Router]
       │                 ▲
       ▼                 │  (Callbacks: onStateChange / onPlayToggle)
 [sequencer.dom.js] ─────┘
       │
       ▼ (Passes state references)
 [sequencer.functionality.js]
       │
       ├─► [sequencer.grammar.parser.js] (Converts Text String Grammar ──► Frequencies)
       │
       └─► [audio.engine.js] (Renders low-level Frequencies ──► Web Audio Nodes)

2. Operational Rules & Maintenance Checklist
Adding Global System States: All future expansions (e.g., custom tuning temperament arrays, root tonic definitions, or FM operator metrics) must be initialized inside the core orchestrator state located in index.html under the appState.sequencerState payload wrapper.
Extending the Audio Profile Array: When creating brand-new physical acoustics or modular synthesis models, add the profile handler logic directly inside audio.engine.js beneath the playToneGroup function blocks. Ensure any corresponding dropdown selection label matches the selection string exactly inside the voicesList array located in sequencer.dom.js.
Timing Cycle Modifiers: Tempo modifications cleanly adjust runtime loops on-the-fly. If an active system timing cycle is processing, it drops out the existing window interval completely and spins up a brand-new target heartbeat without interrupting current play-head steps.

